var definitions = ['<h2>Es ist mein Hut.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it". In this sentence, it functions as the subject.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject with the complement of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German which means "my" in English. It indicates ownership of the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Hut</strong> This is a German noun meaning "hat" in English. It is the object of the sentence and the thing being possessed in this context.</div>','<h2>Meine Familie ist toll.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates possession, showing that the family belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Familie</strong> This is a German noun that translates to "family" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, referred to by the possessive pronoun "Meine".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This word is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the adjective that follows, describing a characteristic of the family.</div><div><strong>toll</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "great" or "fantastic" in English. It describes the speaker’s opinion of their family.</div>','<h2>Meine Brüder sind älter als ich.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, which translates to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation, and it agrees in gender and number with what is being owned; in this case "Brüder" (brothers), which is masculine and plural.</div><div><strong>Brüder</strong> This is the noun for "brothers" in German. It is the plural form of "Bruder", in the nominative case here, serving as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here to describe the state or condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>älter</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "alt" in German, meaning "old". The comparative "älter" translates to "older" in English. It is used here to compare the age of the speaker’s brothers to the speaker him/herself.</div><div><strong>als</strong> This is a conjunction used in German to compare two things, which translates to "than" in English.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the object of the comparison in this sentence.</div>','<h2>Dein Hund ist sehr klug.</h2><div><strong>Dein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "your" in the informal singular form. It implies the dog belongs to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a German noun meaning "dog". It’s the subject of the sentence and is in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the adjective describing it.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "very". It’s used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>klug</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "smart" or "clever". In this sentence, it’s describing the dog’s quality or characteristic.</div>','<h2>Deine Spielsachen sind im Wandschrank.</h2><div><strong>Deine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case and the plural form, indicating ownership of the subject. It means "your" in English and is associated with the second-person singular. It’s the possessive form of "du" (you).</div><div><strong>Spielsachen</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Spielsache", which means "toy" in English. "Spielsachen" translates to "toys", indicating the plural objects that the sentence is talking about.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It functions as the linking verb in this sentence, equating the subject (toys) with their location.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" (meaning "in" or "inside" in English) and the definite article "dem" (meaning "the" in English), which is in the dative case and masculine/neuter singular form. It implies that an object is located within something else, here within the closet.</div><div><strong>Wandschrank</strong> This is a compound noun meaning "closet" in English. "Wand" means "wall" and "Schrank" means "cabinet" or "wardrobe", so "Wandschrank" literally translates to "wall cabinet" and refers to a closet typically mounted or built into a wall.</div>','<h2>Deine Mutter wirkt sehr freundlich.</h2><div><strong>Deine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "your" in the informal second-person singular. It denotes belonging or association with the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Mutter</strong> This is the German word for "mother". It is a noun used to refer to the female parent of a person.</div><div><strong>wirkt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "wirken", which means "to appear" or "to seem". It describes the appearance or the impression that the subject gives off.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>freundlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "friendly". In the sentence, it describes the mother’s demeanor as perceived by the speaker.</div>','<h2>Sein Kajak ist sehr alt, aber das ist ihm egal.</h2><div><strong>Sein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the masculine or neuter third-person singular, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the subject of the sentence, which is "Kajak" in this case.</div><div><strong>Kajak</strong> This is a German noun meaning "kayak". It’s a light, narrow watercraft which is typically propelled by means of a double-bladed paddle. Here, it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject to an adjective or a state of being.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>alt</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "old". It describes the condition of the kayak in the sentence.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neutral demonstrative pronoun or article in German, equivalent to "that" in English. In this sentence, it refers back to the fact that the kayak is very old.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is a repetition of the earlier verb "ist", again acting as the third-person singular present tense form of "sein" to indicate the state of being.</div><div><strong>ihm</strong> This is the dative form of the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "to him" or "for him" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the sentence, in this case, the person to whom the state of the kayak being old is irrelevant.</div><div><strong>egal</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "indifferent" or "does not matter". When combined with "ist ihm", it expresses that the person is unconcerned or indifferent to the condition described in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Seine Eltern gehen mit ihrem Hund zum Park.</h2><div><strong>Seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, meaning "his". It indicates that the following noun "Eltern" (parents) belongs to the male subject being referred to, in the third-person singular.</div><div><strong>Eltern</strong> This is the German word for "parents". It is a plural noun.</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English. It describes the action that the subject (parents) is taking.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "with". It’s used here to introduce the companion (the dog) with whom the action is being done.</div><div><strong>ihrem</strong> This is another possessive pronoun in German, meaning "their". Even though it is form-wise identical to the dative feminine singular and dative neuter singular forms, in this context, it refers to the possessive pronoun in the dative plural because of "Hund" which is a masculine noun.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is the German word for "dog". It is a masculine, singular noun in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>zum</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "zu" (to) and the definite article "dem" (the), forming "to the" in English. "Zu" is used with the dative case in German, and "zum" is specifically used before masculine or neuter singular nouns.</div><div><strong>Park</strong> This is the German word for "park". It is a masculine, singular noun in the dative case, following the preposition "zu" (as part of "zum").</div>','<h2>Mein Freund wäscht sein neues Auto.</h2><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "my" in English, indicating possession or association with the speaker. It is in the masculine nominative singular form here, agreeing with "Freund" (friend).</div><div><strong>Freund</strong> This is a German common noun for "friend". It’s a masculine noun in the nominative case, serving as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wäscht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the German verb "waschen", which means "to wash". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is the reflexive possessive pronoun in German for "his" in English when the subject owns the object. It’s used to indicate that the "neues Auto" (new car) belongs to the "Freund" (friend).</div><div><strong>neues</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "new". It modifies "Auto" and agrees with it in terms of gender, case, and number. In this instance, it’s in the neuter nominative singular form because "Auto" is neuter.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun in the nominative case in German, corresponding to "car" in English. It is the object being washed by the subject of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Ihre Schwester hilft der alten Dame.</h2><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the feminine singular form or the plural form in the nominative or accusative case in German, equivalent to "her" or "their" in English. It indicates possession and agrees in gender and number with the noun it refers to, in this case, "Schwester" (sister).</div><div><strong>Schwester</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German meaning "sister". It’s the subject of the sentence and it’s in the nominative case, indicating that it’s the doer of the action.</div><div><strong>hilft</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "helfen", which means "to help". It describes the action that the subject (Schwester) is performing.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article in the dative case for feminine singular nouns in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here with "alten Dame" to indicate indirect object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>alten</strong> This is an adjective in the dative case for a feminine singular noun in German, meaning "old". It describes the noun "Dame" and agrees with it in number, gender and case.</div><div><strong>Dame</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in the dative case meaning "lady" or "woman" in English. It is the indirect object of the sentence, receiving the action of helping from the subject "Schwester".</div>','<h2>Dies ist Ihre Fahrkarte.</h2><div><strong>Dies</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It’s used to refer to a specific thing or object that is close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Dies" with the predicate "Ihre Fahrkarte".</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. The form "Ihre" denotes formal or polite address and is capitalized as a form of respect.</div><div><strong>Fahrkarte</strong> This is a compound noun in German, which translates to "ticket" in English. It typically refers to a ticket used for public transportation, such as a train or bus.</div>','<h2>Ihr Koffer ist sehr schwer!</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "your" in the formal singular or plural form, corresponding to the English "your". It indicates that the suitcase belongs to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Koffer</strong> This is a German noun meaning "suitcase". It is the subject of the sentence and is masculine gender in German (der Koffer).</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject to its descriptor, indicating its state or condition.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>schwer</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "heavy". In this sentence, it describes the condition or quality of the suitcase.</div>','<h2>Ihre Freunde warten auf sie.</h2><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the third-person plural, or the formal second-person singular "you", equivalent to "their" or "your (formal)" in English, indicating possession. It’s in the feminine or plural nominative/accusative case and agrees with the noun "Freunde" which it modifies.</div><div><strong>Freunde</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Freund" in German, which means "friend". In this sentence, it is the subject, indicating multiple friends are waiting.</div><div><strong>warten</strong> This is the plural third-person present tense form of the verb "warten" in German, which means "to wait". It describes the action being performed by "Ihre Freunde".</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "on", "for", or "about", among others. When followed by "sie", it means "for her" or "for them" depending on the context.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "her" or "them" in English. In this sentence, it is the object of the preposition "auf", revealing who the friends are waiting for.</div>','<h2>Sie vergisst immer ihre Handtasche und ihre Schlüssel.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "she" in the nominative case. It’s the subject of the sentence, referring to a female person.</div><div><strong>vergisst</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "vergessen", which means "to forget". It indicates an ongoing action or habit of the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It indicates that the action of forgetting is a recurring event.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "her" in the accusative case, referring to things that belong to the female subject. In this sentence, it is used twice, each time modifying a different noun.</div><div><strong>Handtasche</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "handbag" or "purse". It is the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of the verb.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is a German coordinating conjunction meaning "and". It connects two noun phrases in the sentence.</div><div><strong>ihre Schlüssel</strong> This phrase consists of the possessive pronoun "ihre" again, followed by the plural noun "Schlüssel", which means "keys". This second phrase is also the direct object of the verb "vergisst", indicating another item that she regularly forgets.</div>','<h2>Ihre Katze spielt mit einem Wollknäuel.</h2><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "Ihre" in German, which means "your" in English when using the formal "you". It indicates possession and agrees with the gender and number of the noun it describes. In this case, it is feminine singular to agree with "Katze".</div><div><strong>Katze</strong> This is the noun "Katze" in German, which means "cat" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is a feminine singular noun.</div><div><strong>spielt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It describes the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is the preposition "mit" in German, which means "with" in English. It’s used here to indicate the participation of another object in the action.</div><div><strong>einem</strong> This is the indefinite article "einem" in German in the dative case, which corresponds to "a" or "an" in English. It is used here because the preposition "mit" requires the dative case.</div><div><strong>Wollknäuel</strong> This is the noun "Wollknäuel" in German, which means "ball of wool" in English. It’s the object of the preposition "mit" and is in the dative case because it follows the preposition "mit".</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Mein Wecker klingelt schon.</h2><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It shows ownership or relation to the subject, which is the speaker.</div><div><strong>Wecker</strong> This is a German noun which means "alarm clock". It is the object possessed by the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>klingelt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "klingeln", which means "to ring" or "to sound". In this sentence, it’s used to indicate that the alarm clock is currently sounding or ringing.</div><div><strong>schon</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "already". It is used to indicate that something has happened sooner than expected or is happening right now.</div>','<h2>Ich will mein Gemüse nicht essen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German first-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This verb translates to "want" in English. It’s the first-person singular present tense form of the German modal verb "wollen", indicating desire or intention.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>Gemüse</strong> This is the German noun for "vegetables". In this sentence, it’s in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "essen".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German negation word, equivalent to "not" in English. It negates the verb or statement that follows it.</div><div><strong>essen</strong> This is the German verb "to eat". In this sentence, it’s in the infinitive form because it’s being used with a modal verb ("will").</div>','<h2>Sie singt mein liebstes Lied.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun for "she". It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>singt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "singen", which means "to sing". It tells us the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the first-person singular possessive pronoun in German, meaning "my". It indicates to whom the "liebstes Lied" belongs.</div><div><strong>liebstes</strong> This is the superlative form of the adjective "lieb" meaning "favorite". As an adjective, it describes the noun "Lied". In this case, it is inflected in the nominative case to match with "Lied".</div><div><strong>Lied</strong> This is the German word for "song". It is the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of being sung.</div>','<h2>Mein Hund brachte mir einen Stock.</h2><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a German noun meaning "dog". Here, it’s in the nominative case and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>brachte</strong> This is the simple past tense form of the German verb "bringen", which means "to bring". It indicates a completed action.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the dative pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "me" in English. In this context, it indicates the indirect object of the sentence, to whom the action is directed.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is an indefinite article in the accusative case in German, used for masculine nouns. It is equivalent to "a" or "an" in English, indicating an unspecified object.</div><div><strong>Stock</strong> This is a German noun meaning "stick". In the sentence, it’s in the accusative case and is the direct object, being the item that was brought.</div>','<h2>Mein Mann ist immer noch im Urlaub.</h2><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, meaning "my". It indicates ownership or association and is used here to denote that the speaker is talking about their husband.</div><div><strong>Mann</strong> This is a German noun meaning "man" or "husband". In this context, it refers to the spouse of the speaker.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It is analogous to "is" in English and describes the state of being.</div><div><strong>immer noch</strong> This is a German adverbial phrase meaning "still". "Immer" means "always", and "noch" means "yet" or "still", combined they emphasize the continuity of the action.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" and the definite article "dem" in German, which translates to "in the" when referring to masculine or neuter nouns in the dative case. Here, it indicates the location or state of being on vacation.</div><div><strong>Urlaub</strong> This is a German noun meaning "vacation" or "holiday". It indicates that someone is taking time off from work or usual duties.</div>','<h2>Ein Film. Mein Freund sieht einen Film.</h2><div><strong>Ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German used for masculine or neuter nouns in the nominative singular. It translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Film</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "film" or "movie". Here, it is the direct object of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German meaning "my". It indicates possession or belonging, agreeing with the masculine or neuter noun that follows it in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>Freund</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "friend". It is the subject of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>sieht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". It describes the action that the subject (the friend) is doing.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is an accusative masculine indefinite article in German. It is used for masculine nouns in the accusative case such as "Film" in the sentence, and it translates as "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Film</strong> Repeated from the first sentence, this masculine noun is here used as the direct object of the verb "sieht", indicating what the friend is watching.</div>','<h2>Mein Hund würde beißen, um uns zu beschützen.</h2><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "my". It indicates ownership or relation to the speaker, and it is masculine or neuter nominative since "Hund" is a masculine noun.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a German noun meaning "dog". It is in the nominative case as it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden" in German, which expresses what would happen under certain conditions. It is used here to form the conditional perfect, indicating a potential, hypothetical action.</div><div><strong>beißen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "beißen" which means "to bite". In this sentence, it’s used together with "würde" to create a conditional phrase.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a German conjunction and preposition which means "in order to". It introduces the purpose or the reason for an action.</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is the accusative form of the German personal pronoun "wir" meaning "us". It is used here in the accusative case as the object indicating who or what is being protected.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a German infinitive marker used before the infinitive form of a verb to express an action that is to be done. It is part of a verb phrase formed with "um" to express the purpose.</div><div><strong>beschützen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "beschützen" meaning "to protect". It is used here after "zu" to complete the phrase indicating the purpose of the dog’s potential action.</div>','<h2>Ich mochte meine Kindheit.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mochte</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "mögen", which in this context means "to like" or "enjoyed". It indicates that the speaker enjoyed something in the past.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German. It is the feminine first-person singular form, used here to modify a noun, making it possessive as in "my". Since "Kindheit" is feminine and singular, "meine" agrees with it in gender and number.</div><div><strong>Kindheit</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "childhood". It’s the direct object of the sentence – what the speaker liked.</div>','<h2>Kennst du meine Schwester?</h2><div><strong>Kennst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "kennen", which means "to know" in English. It indicates familiarity or acquaintance with a person or object.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and denotes the person being spoken to informally.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is the feminine singular form of the possessive pronoun "mein", meaning "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation, showing that the sister is related to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Schwester?</strong> This is the noun for "sister" in German. It is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "kennen", indicating the person that the subject is being asked about.</div>','<h2>Ich muss mir meine Zähne putzen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>muss</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "must" or "have to". It indicates an obligation or necessity.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular reflexive pronoun in the dative case. It is used here reflexively to show that the action of the verb is being done to the subject itself, meaning "myself" in this context.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is a possessive adjective in first-person singular, feminine or plural accusative case, meaning "my" in English. It shows ownership of the teeth ("Zähne").</div><div><strong>Zähne</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Zahn", which means "tooth" in English. The plural form is used here, translating to "teeth".</div><div><strong>putzen</strong> This is the verb in infinitive form meaning "to clean" or "to brush". In this context, it refers to brushing one’s teeth.</div>','<h2>Ich verliere immer meine Schlüssel.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verliere</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "verlieren", which means "to lose". It describes the action being done by the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always" in English. It is used to express the frequency of the action.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the first-person singular, which in this case is in the accusative case due to the direct object that follows. It means "my" in English, indicating ownership of the following noun.</div><div><strong>Schlüssel</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Schlüssel", meaning "keys" in English. As the direct object of the verb "verliere", it follows the possessive pronoun and completes the sentence.</div>','<h2>Er verkaufte meine Wohnung.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verkaufte</strong> This is the simple past tense of the verb "verkaufen", which means "to sell". It indicates a completed action in the past.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the feminine accusative form in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It describes ownership of the apartment by the speaker.</div><div><strong>Wohnung</strong> This is a German noun meaning "apartment". In this sentence, it is the direct object, the thing that was sold by the subject.</div>','<h2>Ich werde meine neue Arbeit lieben.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense form of the auxiliary verb "werden", which is used to form the future tense. It expresses a future action or state.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It’s used here to denote possession of the noun "Arbeit".</div><div><strong>neue</strong> This is an adjective that means "new" in English. It’s used before a noun to describe something that has recently been acquired or has not been known or seen before.</div><div><strong>Arbeit</strong> This is a noun meaning "work" or "job" in English. In this context, it refers to the speaker’s employment.</div><div><strong>lieben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to love" in English. It’s used here in conjunction with the auxiliary verb "werde" to express a future intention of affection or a strong liking towards the speaker’s new job.</div>','<h2>Meine Wohnung ist sehr modern.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>Wohnung</strong> This is a German noun meaning "apartment" or "flat". It’s the object being described in the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject to its description.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>modern</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "modern". It describes a contemporary style or up-to-date character, in this case, of the apartment.</div>','<h2>Meine Tochter zieht sich an.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the first-person singular, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates possession or a relationship to the speaker, and it agrees in gender and number with the noun it describes, which is "Tochter" (daughter) in this case.</div><div><strong>Tochter</strong> This is a noun in German and means "daughter". It is feminine and singular, being the person referred to by the speaker who is performing the action of the verb.</div><div><strong>zieht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ziehen" which, when combined with the reflexive pronoun "sich" forms the reflexive verb "sich anziehen", meaning "to dress oneself" or "to get dressed".</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, which refers back to the subject of the sentence ("Tochter"). It is part of the reflexive verb "sich anziehen".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is part of the separable prefix of the verb "anziehen". In the infinitive, the prefix and the verb are written together, but in a sentence like this, the prefix is separated and placed at the end of the sentence. The prefix "an-" gives the verb "ziehen" a specific meaning related to putting on clothes.</div>','<h2>Dein Auto hat kein Lenkrad.</h2><div><strong>Dein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the second-person singular in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates ownership or possession relating to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a noun meaning "car" in German. It is neuter and is the object being described in the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It describes possession or existence of something.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a combination of "kein", which is a negative indefinite article in German. It negates the existence of something, and in this case, translates to "no" or "not any" in English.</div><div><strong>Lenkrad</strong> This is a noun meaning "steering wheel" in German. It is neuter and is the item that the car is stated to be without in this sentence.</div>','<h2>Dein Hut ist rosa, meiner ist grün.</h2><div><strong>Dein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "your" in the informal singular form, showing ownership or relation to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Hut</strong> This is a noun meaning "hat" in German. It is the subject of the first part of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject "Hut" with the color "rosa" (pink).</div><div><strong>rosa</strong> This is an adjective indicating the color "pink" in German. Here, it describes the hat owned by the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>meiner</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the nominative case for "mine" in German, indicating that the speaker is talking about their own hat. The ending "-er" matches the masculine noun "Hut".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "sein". It’s used here to describe the speaker’s hat.</div><div><strong>grün</strong> This is the adjective for the color "green" in German. It describes the speaker’s hat.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte wissen, wie dein Tag gelaufen ist.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the conjugated form of "mögen" in the first-person singular and in the Konjunktiv II, which expresses a wish or desire. Here, it’s used to mean "would like".</div><div><strong>wissen</strong> This is an infinitive verb in German that means "to know". In combination with "möchte", it expresses the desire to know something.</div><div><strong>wie</strong> This is a German adverb and conjunction that means "how". It introduces a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It’s in the nominative case and it indicates possession or a relationship to the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>Tag</strong> This is a masculine noun in German that means "day". It’s the direct object of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>gelaufen</strong> This is the past participle of "laufen" which means "to run" or "to go". Here, it’s combined with the auxiliary verb "ist" to form the perfect tense, and it is used metaphorically to ask someone how their day went.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of "sein", which means "to be". It is used here as an auxiliary verb to form the perfect tense of "gelaufen".</div>','<h2>Dein Auto ist nicht so schnell wie meins.</h2><div><strong>Dein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the second-person singular, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates ownership or connection to the subject you are talking to.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neutral noun in German which means "car". It’s the thing being possessed in this sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates or reverses the meaning of the verb that follows it.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb which means "as" or "so" in English. In this sentence, it’s used for comparison.</div><div><strong>schnell</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "fast". It describes the speed of the subject, which is the car.</div><div><strong>wie</strong> This is a conjunction or comparison word in German, equivalent to "as" or "like" in English. It’s used here to introduce the term of comparison.</div><div><strong>meins</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German meaning "mine". It refers to the speaker’s own car in this case and is used to compare it to the other person’s car mentioned earlier in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Ach ja! Es ist dein Geburtstag! Tut mir leid.</h2><div><strong>Ach</strong> This is a German interjection often used to express a realization or remembrance. It is similar to the English "oh" or "ah".</div><div><strong>ja</strong> This German word translates to "yes" in English. When used in the context of this sentence, it is often part of expressing that the speaker just remembered something. It can also add emphasis to the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German and means "it". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, which means "your" in English, used here to show possession or relation to the person being addressed. It is in the nominative singular form and used before a masculine or neuter noun.</div><div><strong>Geburtstag</strong> This is a masculine noun in German that means "birthday".</div><div><strong>Tut mir leid</strong> This is a common German phrase meaning "I’m sorry". Literally, it translates to "does me sorrow", where "tut" is the third-person singular present tense form of "tun", meaning "to do", "mir" is the dative form of "ich", meaning "to me", and "leid" is a noun meaning "sorrow" or "regret". In use, it is more similar to saying "I’m sorry" when apologizing for something.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht kann ich dein Auto reparieren.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German word for "perhaps" or "maybe". It indicates a possibility.</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It is used to express ability or permission.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English when addressing someone in a familiar way. It indicates that the car belongs to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a German noun meaning "car" or "automobile". In this sentence, it is the direct object being potentially repaired.</div><div><strong>reparieren</strong> This is a German verb meaning "to repair". It indicates the action being undertaken with respect to the car.</div>','<h2>Und magst du deine Arbeit?</h2><div><strong>Und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>magst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" in English. It indicates the liking or preference of the subject toward an object.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates possession or association with the subject, and it is in the accusative case because it refers to the direct object of the sentence, "Arbeit" (work).</div><div><strong>Arbeit</strong> This is a German noun meaning "work" or "job". It’s the object of the sentence and is in the accusative case following the possessive pronoun "deine".</div>','<h2>Wer sind deine Eltern?</h2><div><strong>Wer</strong> This is the German interrogative pronoun for "who". It is used to ask about the identity of a person or people.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It serves to link the subject to the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is the possessive adjective in the second-person singular, and it is in the accusative case here. It means "your" in English and indicates possession, referring to something that belongs to the person you are speaking to.</div><div><strong>Eltern?</strong> This is a German noun meaning "parents". It is a plural word and the question mark indicates that it is being used in a question.</div>','<h2>Du musst deine Mahlzeit essen.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>musst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "must" or "have to". It is used to express necessity or obligation.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is a possessive adjective in the second-person singular, masculine or feminine form, meaning "your" in English. It modifies the noun "Mahlzeit" to show possession.</div><div><strong>Mahlzeit</strong> This is a noun meaning "meal" in English. It is the object of the sentence, indicating what must be eaten.</div><div><strong>essen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to eat" in English. It is used here with the modal verb "musst" to form the sentence’s predicate.</div>','<h2>Ich bewundere deine Arbeitsmoral.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bewundere</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "bewundern", which means "to admire". It indicates that the speaker is expressing admiration.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is the second-person singular possessive pronoun in the accusative case in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It denotes possession or association with the listener.</div><div><strong>Arbeitsmoral</strong> This is a German noun meaning "work ethic". It combines "Arbeit" (work) and "Moral" (ethic/morality) to denote the moral principles that guide a person’s work habits. Here, it is in the accusative case following the possessive pronoun.</div>','<h2>Sie unterstützten deine Wahl.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is a German personal pronoun in the third-person plural, equivalent to "they" in English. It serves as the subject of the sentence and can also be the formal "you" in the singular or plural, but due to the context, here it’s more likely "they".</div><div><strong>unterstützten</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "unterstützen", which means "to support". Here, it indicates an action that was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the second-person singular, equivalent to "your" in English. It modifies the noun "Wahl" to show possession.</div><div><strong>Wahl</strong> This is a German noun meaning "choice" or "election". In this sentence, it is the direct object being supported.</div>','<h2>Ich werde deine Einladung akzeptieren.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which is used to form the future tense. In English, it can be translated as "will".</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, feminine or neuter singular, which means "your" in English. It shows possession, indicating that the invitation belongs to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Einladung</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in the accusative case. It means "invitation" in English.</div><div><strong>akzeptieren</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb which means "to accept". In this sentence, it is used with the auxiliary verb "werde" to indicate future tense, so it means "will accept" in English.</div>','<h2>Er soll seine Kleider waschen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>soll</strong> This is a modal verb in German, which in this context means "should" or "is supposed to". It’s used here to express a suggestion or obligation.</div><div><strong>seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German which corresponds to "his" in English. It describes ownership or associations with the subject, agreeing with the noun "Kleider" in gender, number, and case.</div><div><strong>Kleider</strong> This is a German noun meaning "clothes". In German, nouns are always capitalized. "Kleider" is plural in this context.</div><div><strong>waschen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to wash". In the sentence, it’s combined with the modal verb "soll" to express what the subject should do.</div>','<h2>Er mag sein brandneues Fahrrad.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". It indicates that he has a liking or preference for something.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, masculine, singular form. It translates to "his" in English and denotes ownership or association with the subject.</div><div><strong>brandneues</strong> This is a compound adjective formed by "brandneu" (brand new) with an -es ending to denote the accusative case, masculine, singular form in German, agreeing with "Fahrrad". It describes something that is completely new.</div><div><strong>Fahrrad</strong> This is a noun which means "bicycle" in English. It is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "mag" – the thing that is liked.</div>','<h2>Er hat sein Zimmer putzen sollen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it’s used to form the perfect tense or compositional past.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, fitting the third-person singular "er" and meaning "his" in English. It indicates that the room (Zimmer) belongs to him.</div><div><strong>Zimmer</strong> This is a noun meaning "room" in English. In this sentence, it’s the direct object of the verbs, showing the location where the action is supposed to take place.</div><div><strong>putzen</strong> This is a verb meaning "to clean" in English. In this sentence, it is an infinitive used together with "sollen" and "hat" to indicate an obligation or something that was supposed to be done.</div><div><strong>sollen</strong> This is a modal verb meaning "should" or "to be supposed to" in English. Here it is used in its infinitive form and works with "hat", creating a sense of a past obligation: He was supposed to clean his room.</div>','<h2>Vermeide, in seine Falle zu tappen.</h2><div><strong>Vermeide</strong> This is the imperative form of the German verb "vermeiden", which means "to avoid". It is being used here to command or advise someone directly.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition which in this context means "into", indicating a movement towards something or into a condition or state.</div><div><strong>seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German which means "his". It indicates ownership or relation to the male subject being referred to.</div><div><strong>Falle</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that translates to "trap". It refers to a trap that is set up to catch something or someone.</div><div><strong>zu tappen</strong> This phrase is a combination of the infinitive "zu" and the verb "tappen". "Zu" is used with an infinitive to create an infinitive phrase, which in English typically maps to "to" plus a verb. "Tappen" translates to "to fall" or "to step" in English, suggesting to step into a trap, metaphorically indicating to be caught or ensnared in something. The phrase "zu tappen" completes the infinitive construction that began with "zu".</div>','<h2>Er kann für sein Alter sehr gut singen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "können", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates ability or possibility in the context of this sentence.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "for". It introduces the phrase "sein Alter" to indicate the reference point for the ability described.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in its masculine singular nominative form, meaning "his". It denotes ownership or association with the subject "Er" (he).</div><div><strong>Alter</strong> This is a noun in German meaning "age". It’s used here in the context of how well the subject can sing relative to his age.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This adverb means "very" in English. It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is an adjective meaning "good" or "well". In the sentence, it describes the manner in which "Er" (he) can sing.</div><div><strong>singen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to sing" in German. It’s the action that "Er" is said to be able to do well.</div>','<h2>Er arbeitet so viel wie sein Kollege.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>arbeitet</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "arbeiten", which means "to work". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>so viel</strong> This phrase translates to "as much" in English. It’s an expression used to compare the extent or degree of an action.</div><div><strong>wie</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "as" or "like", used here for making a comparison between two subjects.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates possession or association with the subject "Er" (he).</div><div><strong>Kollege</strong> This is a German noun meaning "colleague". It’s used here in the singular noun form to refer to a person with whom someone works.</div>','<h2>Nein, ich habe bereits sein Handy angerufen...</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It is used to negate a statement or respond negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It serves as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English, but here it is used as an auxiliary verb to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>bereits</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "already". It indicates that the action has been completed at some time in the past, before now.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the masculine singular form, meaning "his" in English. It indicates possession or association, referring to something that belongs to or is associated with "he" or "him".</div><div><strong>Handy</strong> This is a German loanword from English, adapting the English word "handy" but used to mean "mobile phone" or "cell phone".</div><div><strong>angerufen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "anrufen", which means "to call" in English. In combination with the auxiliary verb "haben", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a past action with relevance to the present.</div>','<h2>Seine Freundin ist am hübschesten.</h2><div><strong>Seine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for the masculine or neuter third-person singular, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates that something belongs to him. In this case, it denotes that the girlfriend (Freundin) is associated with him.</div><div><strong>Freundin</strong> This is a noun in German, which translates to "girlfriend" in English. The noun is feminine singular and is in the nominative case, serving as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This comes from the verb "sein" in German, which means "to be". It is the third-person singular present tense form and links the subject (Seine Freundin) with the predicative (am hübschesten).</div><div><strong>am</strong> This is a contraction of "an dem" in German and is used here with the superlative form. It translates to "at the" or "in the" in English, but in the context of this sentence, it’s part of a fixed phrase used to form the superlative degree of adjectives, similar to "the ... -est" or "the most ..." in English.</div><div><strong>hübschesten</strong> This is the superlative form of the adjective "hübsch", which means "pretty" or "beautiful". The "-esten" ending indicates the superlative degree in German. In this context, it means "the prettiest" or "most beautiful".</div>','<h2>Er hat heute seine ersten Schritte gemacht.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present perfect tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used as an auxiliary verb to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>heute</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "today". It indicates when the action took place.</div><div><strong>seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, masculine singular form of "sein", which means "his". It indicates possession or relationship, referring to something that belongs to "him" (the subject).</div><div><strong>ersten</strong> This is an ordinal number in German, meaning "first". It is the masculine, singular, accusative form of "erster" used to modify the noun "Schritte".</div><div><strong>Schritte</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Schritt", which means "steps". In this context, it refers to the act of walking or moving one’s feet.</div><div><strong>gemacht</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "machen", which means "to make" or "to do". In this sentence, it is used together with the auxiliary verb "hat" to form the past perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div>','<h2>Gut, hier ist Ihr Tisch.</h2><div><strong>Gut</strong> This is a German adjective that means "good". It’s often used in this context as an affirmative reply or to express agreement, similar to saying "Alright" or "Okay" in English.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "here". It indicates the location or place being referred to.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here it is used to link the subject with the location of the table.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "your" in the formal second-person singular or plural form in German. It denotes ownership or association with the person(s) being spoken to formally.</div><div><strong>Tisch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "table". It is the object in this sentence, indicating what is being referred to, in this case, the table assigned or offered to the customer.</div>','<h2>Gut. Wie ist Ihr Name?</h2><div><strong>Gut</strong> This is the German word for "good". It can be used as an affirmative response or to express that something is okay.</div><div><strong>Wie</strong> This is the German interrogative word meaning "how". In the context of this sentence, it is part of the fixed expression "Wie ist Ihr Name?" which means "What is your name?"</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It indicates the state of being or existence.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the formal second-person possessive pronoun in German, which is equivalent to "your" in English. It’s capitalized because it is formal, and in German all formal pronouns are capitalized out of respect.</div><div><strong>Name?</strong> This is the German word for "name". It is a noun that refers to a person’s name. This is the object of the question "Wie ist Ihr Name?" or "What is your name?" in English.</div>','<h2>Ihr Blutdruck ist normal.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the German possessive pronoun in its formal or polite form, equivalent to "your" in English. It is used to address someone respectfully or formally.</div><div><strong>Blutdruck</strong> This is a German compound noun, made from the words "Blut" (blood) and "Druck" (pressure), which together mean "blood pressure".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to connect the subject with the predicate.</div><div><strong>normal</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "normal". It’s used here to describe the state of the blood pressure, indicating that it is within the expected range.</div>','<h2>Kann ich Ihr Rezept sehen?</h2><div><strong>Kann</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It is used here to request permission or the ability to do something.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the formal second-person singular possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English when addressing someone respectfully or formally. In German, the "I" is capitalized.</div><div><strong>Rezept</strong> This German noun means "recipe" or "prescription". In this context, it could mean a medical prescription or a recipe, depending on the context of the conversation.</div><div><strong>sehen?</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". It is used here with "kann" to form a modal verb phrase expressing a request to view or look at something.</div>','<h2>Danke, hier ist Ihr Wechselgeld.</h2><div><strong>Danke</strong> This is the German word for "thanks" or "thank you". It’s an expression of gratitude.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This translates to "here" in English. It indicates the location, referring to the place where the speaker is at the moment or pointing to a specific spot.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It’s used here to link the subject with the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the formal second-person possessive pronoun in German. It’s capitalized because it’s a formal address and translates to "your" in English. In German, "ihr" can also mean "her" or "their", but the capital "I" indicates the formal "your".</div><div><strong>Wechselgeld</strong> This is a German noun meaning "change" as in the money returned to a customer when they have given more than the exact price for an item. It’s a compound word, from "wechseln" (to change) and "Geld" (money).</div>','<h2>Kann ich in Ihr Büro hereinkommen?</h2><div><strong>Kann</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates the ability or possibility to do something.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that, in this context, means "in" or "into", used here to indicate direction towards the inside of a place.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It denotes possession or association with the person being addressed formally.</div><div><strong>Büro</strong> This is a German noun meaning "office". It’s a neutral noun and is the object of the sentence — the place into which the speaker is asking permission to enter.</div><div><strong>hereinkommen?</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German. "Herein" translates to "in" or "inside", and "kommen" means "to come". Combined, the verb "hereinkommen" means "to come in" or "to enter". In this sentence, it is used with a question mark to form a polite request for permission.</div>','<h2>Ihr seht wie eure Eltern aus.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and refers to more than one person.</div><div><strong>seht</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see" or "to look". In this context, it doesn’t pertain to the act of seeing but rather to the appearance of the subject, as part of the expression "aussehen" ("to look like").</div><div><strong>wie</strong> This is a conjunction or relative pronoun in German, which translates to "like" or "as" in English. It is used here to introduce a comparison.</div><div><strong>eure</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the second-person plural in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates possession or belonging to the people addressed (you).</div><div><strong>Eltern</strong> This is a noun meaning "parents" in English. It’s plural and indicates the mother and father or legal guardians of the person or people being addressed.</div><div><strong>aus</strong> When used with "sehen", "aus" is a preposition that is part of the separable verb "aussehen" and means "look like". Separable verbs in German split in certain tenses and constructions. Here, "aus" is placed at the end of the clause.</div>','<h2>Haben Sie Ihre Buchungsnummer?</h2><div><strong>Haben</strong> This is the third-person plural or formal second-person "Sie" present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It is used here to inquire about the possession of something, in this case, the booking number.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for addressing someone in a polite or formal way. It is the subject of the sentence and can refer to a single person or multiple people in formal contexts.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "your" in formal address, corresponding with "Sie". It is feminine or plural due to agreement with "Buchungsnummer", which is feminine. It indicates possession or association with the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>Buchungsnummer</strong> This is a compound noun comprised of "Buchung", which means "booking", and "Nummer", which means "number". Together, "Buchungsnummer" translates to "booking number", a sequence of digits or characters that uniquely identifies a reservation or booking.</div>','<h2>Vielen Dank für Ihre Hilfe!</h2><div><strong>Vielen Dank</strong> This is a common German phrase meaning "many thanks" or "thank you very much". It is used to express gratitude.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "for" in English. It is used to indicate the recipient of thanks or describe the purpose.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the formal German second-person possessive pronoun translating to "your" in English. It’s capitalized here as a sign of formality when addressing someone respectfully in writing.</div><div><strong>Hilfe!</strong> This is a German noun meaning "help" or "assistance". It is used here to specify what the speaker is thankful for.</div>','<h2>Wirklich? Was ist Ihre Zimmernummer?</h2><div><strong>Wirklich?</strong> This is the German word for "really?" or "seriously?". It is used to express surprise or to ask for confirmation of a statement or question.</div><div><strong>Was</strong> This is the German word for "what". It is a question word used to inquire about something.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It is used here as the main verb in the sentence.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the formal second-person possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. The form "Ihre" is used as a polite or formal way to refer to one person’s possessions, reflecting the polite "Sie" form of address.</div><div><strong>Zimmernummer?</strong> This is a compound noun made up of "Zimmer" which means "room" and "Nummer" which means "number". Together, "Zimmernummer" translates to "room number". This is what is being inquired about in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Gut. Haben Sie Ihre Bankkarte?</h2><div><strong>Gut</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "good". In this context, it is used as an interjection to express understanding, agreement, or satisfaction.</div><div><strong>Haben</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here as the main verb of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence and denotes a formal address.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the formal possessive pronoun in the second-person singular or plural in German, meaning "your". It indicates possession, referring to something that belongs to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>Bankkarte</strong> This is a compound noun made of "Bank" (bank) and "Karte" (card), which translates to "bank card". It refers to a debit or credit card provided by a bank to access funds or carry out transactions.</div>','<h2>Gehen Ihre Kinder schon zur Schule?</h2><div><strong>Gehen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English. This is the main verb of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the formal second-person plural possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It’s used to address someone in a polite or formal manner and refers to something that belongs to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>Kinder</strong> This is the German word for "children". It is a plural noun in the nominative case and is the subject of the verb "gehen".</div><div><strong>schon</strong> This is an adverb in German that can mean "already" or "yet" depending on the context. Here, it suggests that the action of going to school has possibly already started or is being queried with the sense of "already".</div><div><strong>zur Schule</strong> This phrase means "to school" in English. "zur" is a contraction of "zu der", which is a preposition meaning "to" followed by the definite article "the" in the feminine dative case, and "Schule", which is the German word for "school" in the singular dative case.</div><div>This German sentence is a question asking if the children of the person being addressed are already attending school.</div>','<h2>Ich habe Ihre Anzeige im Internet gesehen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present perfect tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it’s used to form the present perfect tense, which describes an action that has been completed.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "your" in the formal form of address in German. It’s used to show ownership and is capitalized because all formal pronouns are capitalized in German.</div><div><strong>Anzeige</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "advertisement" or "notice". In this context, it refers to an ad that the speaker has seen.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of "in dem" in German, which translates to "in the" in English. "Im" is a combination of the preposition "in" (meaning "in") and the definite article "dem" (the dative form of "the" for masculine and neuter nouns).</div><div><strong>Internet</strong> This is a neuter noun in German that means "Internet". It is used the same way as in English to refer to the global system of interconnected computer networks.</div><div><strong>gesehen</strong> This is the past participle of "sehen", which means "to see". It’s used in conjunction with "habe" to form the present perfect tense, indicating that the seeing of the advertisement has already occurred.</div>','<h2>Du hast dir ihr neues Album angehört?</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hast</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. In combination with the past participle "angehört", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the dative case of the second-person singular pronoun, "you". In this context, it acts as a reflexive pronoun, showing that the action of the verb is done to oneself.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the feminine third-person singular or plural form, meaning "her" or "their" in English, depending on the context. Here, it refers to her (or their) "new album".</div><div><strong>neues</strong> This is an adjective meaning "new" in English. It agrees in gender (neuter), number (singular), and case (accusative) with the noun it describes, "Album".</div><div><strong>Album</strong> This is the noun for "album" in English, and it is in the accusative case, as it is the direct object of the verb "angehört".</div><div><strong>angehört?</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "anhören", meaning "to listen to" in English. It combines with the auxiliary verb "hast" to form the present perfect tense, creating the meaning "have listened to". The question mark at the end indicates that this is a question.</div>','<h2>Sie wird ihre Hotelzimmertür schließen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, indicating the woman who will perform the action.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "werden", used here to indicate a future tense construction. It translates to "will" in English, used to form the future tense.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in accusative feminine singular form, which means "her" in English. It indicates that the hotel room door belongs to the woman referred to by "sie".</div><div><strong>Hotelzimmertür</strong> This is a German compound noun, combining "Hotelzimmer" (hotel room) and "Tür" (door) to mean "hotel room door". In German, compound nouns are often formed by merging two nouns together.</div><div><strong>schließen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb that means "to close" in English. In this sentence, it’s used together with "wird" to form the future tense, implying that the action will happen.</div>','<h2>Sie weint, weil sie sich ihr Knie verletzt hat.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weint</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "weinen", which means "to cry". It describes the action of the subject.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a conjunction in German meaning "because". It introduces the reason or cause for the action described in the main clause.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case. In this sentence, it refers back to the subject "sie" and is used with the reflexive verb "sich verletzen" (to injure oneself).</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, lady’s version, meaning "her". It indicates possession, showing that the knee belongs to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Knie</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "knee". Here, it’s the direct object of the verb, indicating what was injured.</div><div><strong>verletzt</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "verletzen", which means "to injure". Together with the auxiliary verb "hat" (has), it forms the perfect tense to indicate a completed action.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it’s used as an auxiliary verb to form the perfect tense with the past participle "verletzt".</div>','<h2>Sie mochten ihr Lied, sie sang es sehr gut.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It is also used as the formal second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. In this sentence, "sie" could refer to "they" (regarding a group that liked the song) or to a formal "you" addressing one person.</div><div><strong>mochten</strong> This word is the past tense of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" in English. Here it’s used to describe that the subject liked something in the past.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German meaning "her" in English. It indicates that the song belonged to the female subject of the second independent clause.</div><div><strong>Lied</strong> This is a German noun meaning "song" in English.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English, referring back to the female subject who is singing.</div><div><strong>sang</strong> This is the past tense of the verb "singen", which means "to sing" in English. Here it’s used to indicate that the singing happened in the past.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neutral pronoun "it" in English, referring to the song mentioned earlier.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very" in English.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "well" in English, modifying the way the song was sung.</div>','<h2>Sie sitzt am Strand, um ihre Sorgen zu vergessen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sitzt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sitzen", which means "to sit". It tells us what the subject is doing.</div><div><strong>am Strand</strong> This is a prepositional phrase where "am" is a contraction of "an dem", translating to "at the" in English, and "Strand" means "beach". Put together, "am Strand" means "on the beach" or "at the beach".</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a conjunction used in German to introduce a purpose or objective, equivalent to "in order to" or simply "to" in English.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the third-person feminine singular, meaning "her" in English. It denotes ownership or relation to the subject, which is "sie".</div><div><strong>Sorgen</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Sorge", which means "worries" or "concerns" in English.</div><div><strong>zu vergessen</strong> This is an infinitive construction with "zu" which is used with verbs to express purpose, similar to "to" before a verb in English. "Vergessen" means "to forget", so "zu vergessen" translates to "to forget". The phrase "ihre Sorgen zu vergessen" means "to forget her worries".</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);